/* CCSP :: content/quiz5.js — CCSP Domain 5 question bank (100 items). */
window.CCSP = window.CCSP || {}; CCSP.questions = CCSP.questions || [];
CCSP.questions.push.apply(CCSP.questions, [{"id":"D5-001","domain":5,"obj":"5.1","diff":"easy","q":"A cloud provider must generate and store the master keys that protect tenant encryption keys so that the key material never leaves tamper-resistant hardware. Which component is purpose-built for this role?","options":["A hardware security module (HSM)","A trusted platform module (TPM) soldered to each blade","A software key vault backed by disk encryption","A network security group"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A hardware security module (HSM)</strong> — an HSM is a dedicated, tamper-resistant appliance that generates, stores, and uses cryptographic keys without ever exposing plaintext key material, making it the standard choice for protecting master/root keys.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A trusted platform module (TPM) soldered to each blade</b>: a TPM anchors platform integrity and per-host measurements, not centralized multi-tenant master-key custody.</span><span class='qd'><b>A software key vault backed by disk encryption</b>: keys can still be exposed in host memory and offer no hardware tamper resistance for the master key.</span><span class='qd'><b>A network security group</b>: this is a traffic-filtering control and has nothing to do with key storage.</span>"},{"id":"D5-002","domain":5,"obj":"5.1","diff":"easy","q":"An architect is selecting a hypervisor for a hardened cloud host that will run untrusted tenant workloads directly on server hardware with the smallest possible attack surface. Which hypervisor type best fits?","options":["A Type 2 hypervisor running on a general-purpose desktop OS","A Type 1 (bare-metal) hypervisor","A container runtime sharing the host kernel","An application sandbox inside the guest OS"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A Type 1 (bare-metal) hypervisor</strong> — running directly on hardware with no underlying host OS gives a minimal, purpose-built attack surface, which is why bare-metal hypervisors dominate production cloud infrastructure.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A Type 2 hypervisor running on a general-purpose desktop OS</b>: it inherits the large attack surface and patch burden of the underlying host OS, suited to labs not hardened multi-tenant hosts.</span><span class='qd'><b>A container runtime sharing the host kernel</b>: containers share the kernel and provide weaker isolation than a hypervisor for untrusted tenants.</span><span class='qd'><b>An application sandbox inside the guest OS</b>: this isolates a process, not full tenant VMs on hardware.</span>"},{"id":"D5-003","domain":5,"obj":"5.2","diff":"easy","q":"To administer Linux virtual machines securely over the network, which protocol should operators use for encrypted remote command-line access?","options":["Telnet","FTP","SSH","SNMPv1"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>SSH</strong> — Secure Shell provides encrypted, authenticated remote command-line access and is the standard for administering Linux hosts.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Telnet</b>: transmits credentials and sessions in cleartext, so it must not be used for administration.</span><span class='qd'><b>FTP</b>: is a file-transfer protocol, also cleartext, and does not provide shell access.</span><span class='qd'><b>SNMPv1</b>: is for device monitoring with weak community-string auth, not interactive administration.</span>"},{"id":"D5-004","domain":5,"obj":"5.2","diff":"easy","q":"A security team wants to ensure DNS responses returned to cloud workloads have not been tampered with in transit. Which control directly provides DNS response integrity?","options":["Split-horizon DNS","DHCP snooping","A reverse proxy","DNSSEC"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>DNSSEC</strong> — DNS Security Extensions cryptographically sign records so resolvers can verify that responses are authentic and unmodified.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>DHCP snooping</b>: mitigates rogue DHCP servers on a LAN, not DNS record integrity.</span><span class='qd'><b>A reverse proxy</b>: brokers application traffic and does not sign DNS records.</span><span class='qd'><b>Split-horizon DNS</b>: returns different answers to internal versus external clients but provides no integrity guarantee.</span>"},{"id":"D5-005","domain":5,"obj":"5.2","diff":"easy","q":"An operations team needs a single, hardened entry point through which administrators must connect before reaching internal management interfaces in a private subnet. Which control provides this?","options":["A bastion host (jump box)","A honeypot","A load balancer","A content delivery network"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A bastion host (jump box)</strong> — a bastion is a hardened, monitored gateway that administrators must traverse to reach internal systems, concentrating and controlling administrative access.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A honeypot</b>: is a decoy meant to attract attackers, not a legitimate access gateway.</span><span class='qd'><b>A load balancer</b>: distributes production traffic, not administrative sessions to management planes.</span><span class='qd'><b>A content delivery network</b>: caches and serves content to end users at the edge.</span>"},{"id":"D5-006","domain":5,"obj":"5.3","diff":"easy","q":"Under ITIL, which process is responsible for restoring normal service operation as quickly as possible after a disruption?","options":["Problem management","Incident management","Change management","Capacity management"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Incident management</strong> — its objective is to restore normal service operation as quickly as possible and minimize business impact after a disruption.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Problem management</b>: identifies and removes the underlying root cause, working on a longer horizon than restoration.</span><span class='qd'><b>Change management</b>: governs controlled modifications to the environment, not restoration of a live outage.</span><span class='qd'><b>Capacity management</b>: ensures resources meet demand over time.</span>"},{"id":"D5-007","domain":5,"obj":"5.3","diff":"easy","q":"Which ITIL process seeks to find and eliminate the root cause of recurring incidents so they stop happening?","options":["Incident management","Release management","Problem management","Service level management"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Problem management</strong> — it investigates the underlying cause of one or more incidents and drives permanent elimination of that cause.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Incident management</b>: focuses on rapid restoration, not permanent root-cause removal.</span><span class='qd'><b>Release management</b>: plans and controls the movement of releases into production.</span><span class='qd'><b>Service level management</b>: negotiates and monitors SLAs, not defect elimination.</span>"},{"id":"D5-008","domain":5,"obj":"5.2","diff":"easy","q":"A team wants virtual machines on the same physical host to be logically segmented into separate broadcast domains without adding physical switches. Which technology accomplishes this?","options":["DNSSEC","NAT","A jump box","VLANs"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>VLANs</strong> — virtual LANs partition a switch into isolated broadcast domains, providing logical network segmentation without additional physical hardware.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>NAT</b>: translates addresses at a boundary and does not create separate broadcast domains.</span><span class='qd'><b>A jump box</b>: controls administrative access, not network segmentation.</span><span class='qd'><b>DNSSEC</b>: signs DNS records and is unrelated to Layer-2 segmentation.</span>"},{"id":"D5-009","domain":5,"obj":"5.2","diff":"easy","q":"An organization applies a documented, minimal, standardized secure configuration to every new guest OS image before deployment. What is this practice called?","options":["Baselining","Fuzzing","Load balancing","Tokenization"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Baselining</strong> — establishing and applying a hardened standard configuration to systems is baselining, which reduces configuration drift and attack surface.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Fuzzing</b>: is a software-testing technique that sends malformed input to find defects.</span><span class='qd'><b>Load balancing</b>: distributes traffic across servers.</span><span class='qd'><b>Tokenization</b>: substitutes sensitive data values with non-sensitive tokens.</span>"},{"id":"D5-010","domain":5,"obj":"5.2","diff":"easy","q":"An operations team wants to define its entire cloud network and compute configuration in version-controlled declarative files so environments can be rebuilt identically and reviewed like code. Which approach is this?","options":["Manual console provisioning","Infrastructure as Code (IaC)","Screen scraping","Blue-green load balancing"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Infrastructure as Code (IaC)</strong> — declaring infrastructure in version-controlled, machine-readable files enables repeatable, reviewable, auditable provisioning.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Manual console provisioning</b>: is error-prone, unversioned, and not repeatable.</span><span class='qd'><b>Screen scraping</b>: extracts data from a UI and is unrelated to provisioning.</span><span class='qd'><b>Blue-green load balancing</b>: is a deployment/traffic-switching pattern, not a way to declare infrastructure.</span>"},{"id":"D5-011","domain":5,"obj":"5.2","diff":"easy","q":"Which network security control passively detects and alerts on suspicious traffic but does not, by itself, block it?","options":["An intrusion prevention system (IPS)","A stateful firewall","An intrusion detection system (IDS)","A network security group"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>An intrusion detection system (IDS)</strong> — an IDS monitors and alerts on suspicious activity but takes no automatic blocking action.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>An intrusion prevention system (IPS)</b>: sits inline and actively blocks malicious traffic, going beyond detection.</span><span class='qd'><b>A stateful firewall</b>: enforces allow/deny rules rather than passively alerting on anomalies.</span><span class='qd'><b>A network security group</b>: is a rule-based filtering construct that permits or denies, not an alerting sensor.</span>"},{"id":"D5-012","domain":5,"obj":"5.1","diff":"easy","q":"Which chip provides a hardware root of trust on an individual server, storing measurements used to verify the host booted a trusted software stack?","options":["HSM","WAF","CASB","TPM"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>TPM</strong> — a Trusted Platform Module is a per-host chip that stores boot measurements and supports attestation, anchoring the platform's root of trust.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>HSM</b>: is a centralized appliance for key custody, not a per-host boot-integrity anchor.</span><span class='qd'><b>CASB</b>: is a cloud access security broker mediating SaaS usage.</span><span class='qd'><b>WAF</b>: is a web application firewall inspecting HTTP traffic.</span>"},{"id":"D5-013","domain":5,"obj":"5.3","diff":"easy","q":"Under ITIL, which process maintains accurate records of configuration items and their relationships, typically in a CMDB?","options":["Configuration management","Change management","Availability management","Release management"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Configuration management</strong> — it identifies, controls, and records configuration items and their interdependencies, usually within a configuration management database (CMDB).<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Change management</b>: authorizes and controls changes but does not itself maintain the CI inventory.</span><span class='qd'><b>Availability management</b>: ensures services meet agreed availability targets.</span><span class='qd'><b>Release management</b>: packages and deploys releases into production.</span>"},{"id":"D5-014","domain":5,"obj":"5.2","diff":"easy","q":"A SOC wants to aggregate and correlate logs from firewalls, hosts, and applications to detect multi-source attack patterns. Which platform is designed for this?","options":["A CMDB","A SIEM","A honeypot","A DHCP server"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A SIEM</strong> — Security Information and Event Management platforms centralize, normalize, and correlate log data across sources to surface security events.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A CMDB</b>: stores configuration item records, not correlated security events.</span><span class='qd'><b>A honeypot</b>: is a decoy for luring attackers, not a correlation engine.</span><span class='qd'><b>A DHCP server</b>: assigns IP addresses and provides no security analytics.</span>"},{"id":"D5-015","domain":5,"obj":"5.2","diff":"easy","q":"To keep a clustered set of virtualization hosts continuously available, an operator enables a feature that automatically restarts VMs on a surviving host if their host fails. What is this feature commonly called?","options":["Maintenance mode","DNSSEC","High availability (HA)","Tokenization"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>High availability (HA)</strong> — cluster HA automatically restarts affected VMs on healthy hosts after a host failure, minimizing downtime.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Maintenance mode</b>: gracefully evacuates a host for planned servicing; it does not respond to unplanned failures.</span><span class='qd'><b>DNSSEC</b>: provides DNS integrity, unrelated to cluster failover.</span><span class='qd'><b>Tokenization</b>: is a data-protection technique.</span>"},{"id":"D5-016","domain":5,"obj":"5.1","diff":"medium","q":"A CCSP is standing up a fleet of hardened hypervisor hosts and wants consistent, auditable configuration applied at build time rather than by hand. Which practice best supports repeatable, drift-free host builds?","options":["Manually configuring each host and documenting steps in a wiki","Cloning one manually built golden image and never updating it","Allowing each administrator to tune hosts to their preference","Using installation and configuration management tools driven by version-controlled definitions"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Using installation and configuration management tools driven by version-controlled definitions</strong> — automated, code-driven configuration produces consistent, auditable, repeatable host builds and detects drift.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Manually configuring each host and documenting steps in a wiki</b>: relies on human accuracy and drifts quickly across a fleet.</span><span class='qd'><b>Allowing each administrator to tune hosts to their preference</b>: guarantees inconsistency and unauditable configurations.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cloning one manually built golden image and never updating it</b>: freezes in vulnerabilities and cannot track ongoing changes.</span>"},{"id":"D5-017","domain":5,"obj":"5.2","diff":"medium","q":"An administrator must occasionally reach a management interface that has no public exposure. Security wants the connection point isolated, heavily logged, and MFA-gated. Which design most directly satisfies this?","options":["Requiring all admin sessions to traverse a hardened, logged bastion host with MFA","Publishing the management interface behind a WAF","Opening SSH to the management subnet from the corporate IP range","Placing the management interface in the same subnet as production workloads"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Requiring all admin sessions to traverse a hardened, logged bastion host with MFA</strong> — a bastion concentrates administrative access at one controlled, monitored, MFA-protected choke point that never exposes the management plane directly.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Publishing the management interface behind a WAF</b>: a WAF inspects web application traffic and does not provide gated interactive admin access.</span><span class='qd'><b>Opening SSH to the management subnet from the corporate IP range</b>: a broad source range still exposes the plane and weakens accountability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Placing the management interface in the same subnet as production workloads</b>: collapses segmentation and increases blast radius.</span>"},{"id":"D5-018","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"medium","q":"A SOC analyst notices that firewall, endpoint, and identity logs each look benign individually, but together suggest lateral movement. Which capability is essential to reveal this attack?","options":["Log retention on each source system","Cross-source correlation in a SIEM","A faster stateful firewall","A larger honeypot network"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Cross-source correlation in a SIEM</strong> — correlating events across firewall, endpoint, and identity data is exactly how multi-stage activity like lateral movement is surfaced when single sources appear benign.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Log retention on each source system</b>: keeping logs is necessary but does not by itself correlate or detect the pattern.</span><span class='qd'><b>A faster stateful firewall</b>: throughput does not reveal cross-domain behavioral chains.</span><span class='qd'><b>A larger honeypot network</b>: attracts attackers to decoys but does not correlate the real production telemetry described.</span>"},{"id":"D5-019","domain":5,"obj":"5.3","diff":"medium","q":"An urgent security patch must be deployed to fix an actively exploited flaw, but the change board meets weekly. Which ITIL mechanism allows the fix to proceed under controlled authorization?","options":["A standard change","A normal change scheduled for the next window","An emergency change via the ECAB","A retrospective problem record"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>An emergency change via the ECAB</strong> — ITIL provides an Emergency Change Advisory Board path so critical, time-sensitive changes get expedited but still authorized and recorded.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A standard change</b>: is pre-approved and low-risk; an actively exploited flaw fix is not a routine pre-authorized change.</span><span class='qd'><b>A normal change scheduled for the next window</b>: delays remediation of an active exploit unacceptably.</span><span class='qd'><b>A retrospective problem record</b>: documents root cause after the fact and does not authorize deploying the patch now.</span>"},{"id":"D5-020","domain":5,"obj":"5.2","diff":"medium","q":"A cloud team wants east-west traffic between application tiers on the same virtual network to be inspected and filtered, not just north-south traffic at the perimeter. Which control most directly addresses intra-tier filtering?","options":["A single perimeter firewall","DNSSEC on the internal zone","A CDN in front of the application","Network security groups applied per workload/tier"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Network security groups applied per workload/tier</strong> — per-workload NSGs enforce granular allow/deny rules on east-west traffic between tiers, not just at the perimeter.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A single perimeter firewall</b>: inspects north-south traffic and typically misses lateral, intra-network flows.</span><span class='qd'><b>A CDN in front of the application</b>: handles inbound edge delivery, not internal tier-to-tier traffic.</span><span class='qd'><b>DNSSEC on the internal zone</b>: ensures DNS integrity but does not filter workload traffic.</span>"},{"id":"D5-021","domain":5,"obj":"5.2","diff":"medium","q":"An operator must maintain a consistent, defensible patch cadence across hundreds of ephemeral cloud instances that are frequently created and destroyed. Which strategy best ensures instances launch already patched?","options":["Baking patched, hardened images and redeploying instances from them","Patching instances individually after they boot","Disabling automatic instance replacement to keep patches stable","Relying on end users to trigger patch installs"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Baking patched, hardened images and redeploying instances from them</strong> — immutable, pre-patched golden images ensure every ephemeral instance starts current, which scales far better than in-place patching.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Patching instances individually after they boot</b>: leaves a vulnerable window and does not scale for short-lived instances.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling automatic instance replacement to keep patches stable</b>: undermines elasticity and prevents refreshing images with new patches.</span><span class='qd'><b>Relying on end users to trigger patch installs</b>: is unreliable and inappropriate for infrastructure.</span>"},{"id":"D5-022","domain":5,"obj":"5.1","diff":"medium","q":"A tenant requires assurance that its VM will only run on a physical host whose boot integrity has been cryptographically verified. Which combination supports this trusted-launch requirement?","options":["A software firewall plus antivirus on the guest","A TPM providing measured boot with remote attestation","A load balancer with health checks","A DNSSEC-signed internal zone"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A TPM providing measured boot with remote attestation</strong> — a TPM records boot measurements that a relying party can verify via attestation, giving assurance the host booted a trusted stack before workloads run.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A software firewall plus antivirus on the guest</b>: protects the guest at runtime but says nothing about host boot integrity.</span><span class='qd'><b>A load balancer with health checks</b>: verifies service reachability, not platform integrity.</span><span class='qd'><b>A DNSSEC-signed internal zone</b>: ensures DNS integrity, unrelated to host boot trust.</span>"},{"id":"D5-023","domain":5,"obj":"5.3","diff":"medium","q":"After a series of related outages, management asks the team to formally track the investigation and permanent fix separate from day-to-day restoration tickets. Which two ITIL processes are being distinguished?","options":["Change and release management","Capacity and availability management","Incident (restore) and problem (root cause) management","Configuration and deployment management"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Incident (restore) and problem (root cause) management</strong> — incident management restores service quickly while problem management investigates and permanently eliminates the underlying cause; the request separates these two.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Change and release management</b>: govern modifying and deploying services, not restoration versus root cause.</span><span class='qd'><b>Capacity and availability management</b>: address resourcing and uptime targets, not this incident/problem split.</span><span class='qd'><b>Configuration and deployment management</b>: track CIs and move releases, not the restore/root-cause distinction.</span>"},{"id":"D5-024","domain":5,"obj":"5.2","diff":"medium","q":"To reduce risk on a cluster, an operator wants to service a busy host by first migrating its running VMs off with no downtime, then taking it offline. Which feature should be used?","options":["High availability failover","Storage tokenization","A honeypot redirect","Maintenance mode with live migration"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Maintenance mode with live migration</strong> — placing a host in maintenance mode evacuates its running VMs via live migration to other hosts before it is taken offline for planned servicing.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>High availability failover</b>: reacts to unplanned host failure by restarting VMs, causing an interruption rather than a graceful planned evacuation.</span><span class='qd'><b>A honeypot redirect</b>: is a decoy mechanism unrelated to host servicing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Storage tokenization</b>: is a data-protection technique, not a compute-maintenance action.</span>"},{"id":"D5-025","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"medium","q":"A CCSP is designing continuous monitoring for a cloud SOC. Which set of sources best supports 'intelligent monitoring' aimed at early threat detection?","options":["Firewalls, IDS/IPS, network security groups, and honeypots feeding analytics","Only application access logs","Only billing and metering data","Only physical badge-reader logs"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Firewalls, IDS/IPS, network security groups, and honeypots feeding analytics</strong> — combining perimeter, detection, segmentation, and deception telemetry into analytics is the CCSP notion of intelligent monitoring.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Only application access logs</b>: is too narrow to detect network-level or deception-based threats.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only billing and metering data</b>: supports cost management, not threat detection.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only physical badge-reader logs</b>: covers facility access, missing the network and host threat picture.</span>"},{"id":"D5-026","domain":5,"obj":"5.4","diff":"medium","q":"During forensic acquisition of a running cloud VM suspected of compromise, which action best preserves the most volatile and legally defensible evidence first?","options":["Immediately power off the VM to freeze disk state","Capture a memory (RAM) snapshot before altering the running system","Delete suspicious files to stop the attack","Reboot the VM into a clean image"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Capture a memory (RAM) snapshot before altering the running system</strong> — following order of volatility, volatile memory must be acquired first because powering off or rebooting destroys it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Immediately power off the VM to freeze disk state</b>: destroys volatile memory evidence and may trigger anti-forensic actions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Delete suspicious files to stop the attack</b>: spoliates evidence and breaks chain of custody.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reboot the VM into a clean image</b>: wipes the volatile state investigators need.</span>"},{"id":"D5-027","domain":5,"obj":"5.4","diff":"medium","q":"An investigator must demonstrate that cloud evidence was handled without unauthorized alteration from collection to court. Which practice most directly provides this assurance?","options":["Encrypting the evidence at rest only","Storing evidence on the same tenant that was compromised","Maintaining a documented chain of custody with hash verification","Relying on the provider's marketing SOC 3 report"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Maintaining a documented chain of custody with hash verification</strong> — a continuous custody record plus cryptographic hashing proves integrity and unbroken control of the evidence.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypting the evidence at rest only</b>: protects confidentiality but does not prove an unbroken custody trail or detect tampering.</span><span class='qd'><b>Storing evidence on the same tenant that was compromised</b>: risks contamination and further tampering.</span><span class='qd'><b>Relying on the provider's marketing SOC 3 report</b>: is a general-audience attestation, not evidence-handling proof.</span>"},{"id":"D5-028","domain":5,"obj":"5.5","diff":"medium","q":"A confirmed breach in a cloud service exposes customer personal data. Beyond internal response, which communication obligation must the CCSP ensure is coordinated first with the appropriate parties?","options":["A press release to all social media channels","A public root-cause blog post before investigation completes","An immediate refund to all customers","Notification of affected customers and regulators per contractual and legal requirements"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Notification of affected customers and regulators per contractual and legal requirements</strong> — breach communication must be driven by contractual SLAs and legal/regulatory breach-notification duties to the right stakeholders.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A press release to all social media channels</b>: broad publicity is not the required, structured notification and may harm the response.</span><span class='qd'><b>An immediate refund to all customers</b>: is a business decision, not the mandated breach-communication obligation.</span><span class='qd'><b>A public root-cause blog post before investigation completes</b>: risks releasing inaccurate information and violating disclosure timing.</span>"},{"id":"D5-029","domain":5,"obj":"5.2","diff":"medium","q":"An organization wants to detect attackers who have breached the perimeter by luring them toward a deliberately vulnerable-looking system that holds no production data. Which control fits?","options":["A honeypot","A bastion host","A DNSSEC resolver","A storage cluster"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A honeypot</strong> — a honeypot is a decoy designed to attract and observe attackers, providing high-signal detection of activity that has bypassed other controls.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A bastion host</b>: is a legitimate hardened access gateway, not a decoy.</span><span class='qd'><b>A DNSSEC resolver</b>: verifies DNS integrity, not attacker deception.</span><span class='qd'><b>A storage cluster</b>: provides resilient storage, not detection.</span>"},{"id":"D5-030","domain":5,"obj":"5.2","diff":"medium","q":"An operations team needs to secure remote administrative access to Windows servers while ensuring sessions are encrypted and centrally brokered. Which combination is most appropriate?","options":["RDP exposed directly to the internet","RDP tunneled through a bastion/gateway with TLS and MFA","Telnet through a VPN","FTP over a jump box"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>RDP tunneled through a bastion/gateway with TLS and MFA</strong> — brokering RDP through a hardened gateway with encryption and MFA keeps the management plane off the public internet while enforcing strong access control.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>RDP exposed directly to the internet</b>: is a well-known attack magnet and violates least exposure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Telnet through a VPN</b>: Telnet is cleartext and is not an administrative protocol for Windows servers.</span><span class='qd'><b>FTP over a jump box</b>: FTP is a file-transfer protocol, not remote administration, and is typically cleartext.</span>"},{"id":"D5-031","domain":5,"obj":"5.2","diff":"medium","q":"A CCSP reviews a cluster's resource-scheduling feature that automatically rebalances VM placement across hosts to optimize performance and avoid contention. Which capability is described?","options":["Maintenance mode","Cryptographic erase","Distributed resource scheduling / dynamic optimization","DHCP snooping"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Distributed resource scheduling / dynamic optimization</strong> — this capability continuously rebalances workloads across cluster hosts to optimize performance and avoid resource contention.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Maintenance mode</b>: evacuates a single host for servicing rather than continuously optimizing placement.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cryptographic erase</b>: is a data-destruction technique.</span><span class='qd'><b>DHCP snooping</b>: mitigates rogue DHCP servers, unrelated to VM placement.</span>"},{"id":"D5-032","domain":5,"obj":"5.3","diff":"medium","q":"An ITIL-aligned cloud team wants a formal, ongoing mechanism to measure service performance and drive incremental improvements over time. Which process provides this?","options":["Incident management","Capacity management","Deployment management","Continual service improvement (CSI)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Continual service improvement (CSI)</strong> — CSI is the ITIL practice that continually measures and improves services, processes, and capabilities over time.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Incident management</b>: restores service after disruptions rather than driving ongoing improvement.</span><span class='qd'><b>Deployment management</b>: moves releases into the live environment.</span><span class='qd'><b>Capacity management</b>: matches resources to demand but is narrower than overall improvement.</span>"},{"id":"D5-033","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"medium","q":"A vulnerability assessment of a cloud environment returns hundreds of findings. To manage security operations effectively, how should the CCSP prioritize remediation?","options":["Prioritize by risk, weighting exploitability and business impact","Fix findings alphabetically by hostname","Fix only the lowest-severity items first to build momentum","Ignore findings without a public exploit"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Prioritize by risk, weighting exploitability and business impact</strong> — risk-based prioritization focuses limited remediation effort where likelihood and impact are greatest.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Fix findings alphabetically by hostname</b>: ignores severity and business context entirely.</span><span class='qd'><b>Fix only the lowest-severity items first to build momentum</b>: leaves the most dangerous exposures open longest.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore findings without a public exploit</b>: dismisses real risk, since exploits can emerge or be non-public.</span>"},{"id":"D5-034","domain":5,"obj":"5.2","diff":"medium","q":"A team must ensure that backups of cloud workloads are actually usable for recovery. Which practice most directly validates recoverability?","options":["Encrypting backups with a rotated key","Periodically performing test restores from backups","Storing backups in the same volume as production","Increasing backup frequency only"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Periodically performing test restores from backups</strong> — only actually restoring data proves backups are complete, uncorrupted, and recoverable within objectives.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypting backups with a rotated key</b>: protects confidentiality but does not prove the backup can be restored.</span><span class='qd'><b>Storing backups in the same volume as production</b>: exposes them to the same failure and defeats resilience.</span><span class='qd'><b>Increasing backup frequency only</b>: creates more copies without confirming any of them restore.</span>"},{"id":"D5-035","domain":5,"obj":"5.1","diff":"medium","q":"When provisioning virtual hardware for a security-sensitive workload, which configuration decision most directly limits an attacker's ability to pivot between tenant VMs sharing a host?","options":["Allocating more vCPUs to the workload","Increasing the guest's memory","Enforcing strong hypervisor-level isolation and disabling unneeded inter-VM channels","Assigning a public IP to each VM"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Enforcing strong hypervisor-level isolation and disabling unneeded inter-VM channels</strong> — hardening the hypervisor and removing shared channels directly reduces the risk of VM escape and cross-tenant pivoting.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Allocating more vCPUs to the workload</b>: affects performance, not isolation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Increasing the guest's memory</b>: is a capacity choice with no isolation benefit.</span><span class='qd'><b>Assigning a public IP to each VM</b>: increases exposure rather than limiting lateral movement.</span>"},{"id":"D5-036","domain":5,"obj":"5.2","diff":"medium","q":"A cloud network design must protect data in transit between microservices and the management plane. Which control set is the correct baseline?","options":["Cleartext HTTP with IP allowlists","MAC filtering only","NAT alone","Mutual TLS for service traffic and VPN/TLS for management access"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Mutual TLS for service traffic and VPN/TLS for management access</strong> — encrypting and mutually authenticating service traffic plus tunneling management over TLS/VPN protects confidentiality and integrity in transit.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Cleartext HTTP with IP allowlists</b>: leaves traffic unencrypted and interceptable regardless of source filtering.</span><span class='qd'><b>NAT alone</b>: only translates addresses and provides no encryption.</span><span class='qd'><b>MAC filtering only</b>: is easily spoofed and offers no confidentiality.</span>"},{"id":"D5-037","domain":5,"obj":"5.3","diff":"medium","q":"A change to a production cloud service went badly and caused an outage. ITIL best practice requires that every authorized change include which element to limit such impact?","options":["A documented back-out (rollback) plan","A marketing announcement","A price change","A new SLA tier"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A documented back-out (rollback) plan</strong> — ITIL change management requires a tested rollback plan so a failed change can be reversed to restore service quickly.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A marketing announcement</b>: is unrelated to controlling change risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>A price change</b>: is a commercial matter, not a change-safety requirement.</span><span class='qd'><b>A new SLA tier</b>: adjusts service commitments but does not mitigate a failed change.</span>"},{"id":"D5-038","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"hard","q":"A 24x7 cloud SOC is overwhelmed by alert volume, with real incidents lost among noise. Which improvement most directly and sustainably raises detection quality without simply hiring more analysts?","options":["Forwarding every raw log line to analysts by email","Tuning correlation rules and adding automated triage/enrichment in the SIEM","Disabling the noisiest sensors entirely","Raising all alert thresholds to the maximum"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Tuning correlation rules and adding automated triage/enrichment in the SIEM</strong> — refining detection logic and automating enrichment reduces false positives and surfaces true incidents, improving quality at scale.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Forwarding every raw log line to analysts by email</b>: increases noise and worsens the overload.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling the noisiest sensors entirely</b>: creates blind spots and may drop critical telemetry.</span><span class='qd'><b>Raising all alert thresholds to the maximum</b>: suppresses noise but also hides real low-and-slow attacks.</span>"},{"id":"D5-039","domain":5,"obj":"5.4","diff":"hard","q":"A CCSP must acquire forensic evidence from a IaaS VM but the underlying host and hypervisor are controlled by the provider. Which factor is the single greatest constraint on the investigator's ability to collect complete evidence?","options":["The guest OS version","The color of the console theme","The provider-controlled abstraction limiting access to underlying artifacts","The VM's assigned hostname"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The provider-controlled abstraction limiting access to underlying artifacts</strong> — in cloud forensics the customer typically cannot reach hypervisor, host, or physical-layer artifacts, so provider cooperation and contractual terms constrain evidence completeness.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The guest OS version</b>: affects tooling choices but is not the fundamental access barrier.</span><span class='qd'><b>The color of the console theme</b>: is irrelevant to evidence collection.</span><span class='qd'><b>The VM's assigned hostname</b>: is a label with no bearing on forensic reach.</span>"},{"id":"D5-040","domain":5,"obj":"5.2","diff":"hard","q":"An architect is designing management-plane security for a large multi-account cloud estate. Which principle most reduces the risk that a single compromised administrator credential can reconfigure the entire environment?","options":["Sharing one powerful admin account for convenience","Granting all engineers standing global admin rights","Storing admin credentials in a shared spreadsheet","Enforcing least privilege, role separation, and just-in-time privileged access to the management plane"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Enforcing least privilege, role separation, and just-in-time privileged access to the management plane</strong> — scoping privileges narrowly and granting elevation only when needed limits the blast radius of any single compromised credential.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Sharing one powerful admin account for convenience</b>: destroys accountability and maximizes blast radius.</span><span class='qd'><b>Storing admin credentials in a shared spreadsheet</b>: exposes credentials broadly and defeats access control.</span><span class='qd'><b>Granting all engineers standing global admin rights</b>: makes every account a full-control target.</span>"},{"id":"D5-041","domain":5,"obj":"5.3","diff":"hard","q":"A cloud provider's ISO/IEC 20000-1-aligned service management program must connect availability targets, resource forecasting, and customer commitments coherently. Which mapping of processes to that goal is correct?","options":["Availability management sets uptime targets; capacity management forecasts resources; service level management holds the SLA commitments","Incident management sets uptime targets; problem management forecasts resources; change management holds the SLA","Release management sets uptime targets; deployment management forecasts resources; configuration management holds the SLA","Continuity management sets uptime targets; security management forecasts resources; incident management holds the SLA"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Availability management sets uptime targets; capacity management forecasts resources; service level management holds the SLA commitments</strong> — this is the correct ITIL/ISO 20000-1 alignment of availability, capacity, and SLA processes.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Incident management sets uptime targets; problem management forecasts resources; change management holds the SLA</b>: misassigns restoration, root-cause, and change processes to planning roles they do not own.</span><span class='qd'><b>Release management sets uptime targets; deployment management forecasts resources; configuration management holds the SLA</b>: confuses delivery processes with availability, capacity, and SLA ownership.</span><span class='qd'><b>Continuity management sets uptime targets; security management forecasts resources; incident management holds the SLA</b>: continuity plans for disasters and security manages controls; neither sets routine uptime targets or forecasts capacity.</span>"},{"id":"D5-042","domain":5,"obj":"5.1","diff":"hard","q":"A regulated tenant demands that even the cloud provider's administrators cannot read the tenant's key material at rest or in use. Which architectural choice most directly satisfies this while keeping keys usable?","options":["Provider-managed keys stored in the provider's database","Customer keys generated and used inside a dedicated HSM under customer control (BYOK/HYOK with HSM backing)","Keys embedded in application source code","Keys emailed to administrators for backup"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Customer keys generated and used inside a dedicated HSM under customer control (BYOK/HYOK with HSM backing)</strong> — HSM-backed customer-controlled keys keep plaintext key material inside tamper-resistant hardware the provider's staff cannot extract, while still allowing cryptographic use.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Provider-managed keys stored in the provider's database</b>: leaves key custody and potential access with the provider, failing the requirement.</span><span class='qd'><b>Keys embedded in application source code</b>: exposes keys to anyone with code access and is a severe anti-pattern.</span><span class='qd'><b>Keys emailed to administrators for backup</b>: broadly discloses key material and destroys confidentiality.</span>"},{"id":"D5-043","domain":5,"obj":"5.2","diff":"hard","q":"A high-availability cluster spans two availability zones. During a zone outage, VMs restart in the surviving zone, but performance degrades badly. What design gap most likely caused the degradation, and what is the correct remediation?","options":["Too many VLANs; remove segmentation","DNSSEC misconfiguration; disable DNSSEC","Insufficient reserved capacity in the surviving zone; enforce admission control / capacity reservation for failover","Excessive logging; stop collecting logs"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Insufficient reserved capacity in the surviving zone; enforce admission control / capacity reservation for failover</strong> — HA only works if the surviving zone has reserved headroom to absorb the failed zone's load; admission control/capacity reservation guarantees it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Too many VLANs; remove segmentation</b>: segmentation does not cause capacity-driven performance loss and removing it weakens security.</span><span class='qd'><b>DNSSEC misconfiguration; disable DNSSEC</b>: DNS integrity is unrelated to post-failover CPU/memory contention.</span><span class='qd'><b>Excessive logging; stop collecting logs</b>: logging overhead is not the driver of failover capacity shortfalls and removing logs harms operations.</span>"},{"id":"D5-044","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"hard","q":"During incident response to a cloud compromise, the SOC wants to contain the threat without destroying evidence needed for later forensics and possible litigation. Which containment approach best balances both goals?","options":["Immediately terminate and delete all affected instances","Restore from backup over the running systems immediately","Leave systems fully connected to keep monitoring","Isolate affected instances via network controls while snapshotting memory and disk for evidence"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Isolate affected instances via network controls while snapshotting memory and disk for evidence</strong> — network isolation contains the threat while preserving live and disk state for forensics, balancing containment with evidentiary needs.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Immediately terminate and delete all affected instances</b>: contains the threat but destroys evidence and breaks chain of custody.</span><span class='qd'><b>Leave systems fully connected to keep monitoring</b>: risks continued attacker action and data exfiltration.</span><span class='qd'><b>Restore from backup over the running systems immediately</b>: overwrites the compromised state investigators must examine.</span>"},{"id":"D5-045","domain":5,"obj":"5.5","diff":"hard","q":"A multinational cloud provider suffers an incident affecting customers in several jurisdictions with differing breach-notification timelines. How should the CCSP govern stakeholder communication?","options":["Map obligations per jurisdiction and stakeholder, notifying each within its specific legal and contractual deadline","Apply a single global timeline chosen for convenience","Delay all notifications until every investigation closes","Let each regional team decide independently with no coordination"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Map obligations per jurisdiction and stakeholder, notifying each within its specific legal and contractual deadline</strong> — differing regimes require a coordinated matrix so each party is notified within its own applicable deadline.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Apply a single global timeline chosen for convenience</b>: risks missing stricter jurisdictional deadlines and non-compliance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Delay all notifications until every investigation closes</b>: violates statutory notification windows that start before investigations complete.</span><span class='qd'><b>Let each regional team decide independently with no coordination</b>: produces inconsistent, conflicting messaging and gaps.</span>"},{"id":"D5-046","domain":5,"obj":"5.2","diff":"hard","q":"An IaC pipeline lets developers deploy infrastructure rapidly, but a misconfigured template exposed a storage bucket publicly. Which control best prevents insecure infrastructure from reaching production while preserving IaC speed?","options":["Requiring all deployments to be done manually again","Automated policy-as-code / security scanning of IaC templates in the CI/CD pipeline before apply","Removing version control from the templates","Letting developers self-approve their own changes"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Automated policy-as-code / security scanning of IaC templates in the CI/CD pipeline before apply</strong> — scanning templates against security policy before deployment catches misconfigurations early while keeping the pipeline fast.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Requiring all deployments to be done manually again</b>: discards IaC's benefits and introduces human error.</span><span class='qd'><b>Removing version control from the templates</b>: eliminates review, auditability, and rollback.</span><span class='qd'><b>Letting developers self-approve their own changes</b>: removes independent oversight and enables the exact misconfiguration described.</span>"},{"id":"D5-047","domain":5,"obj":"5.3","diff":"hard","q":"A provider bundles a large set of related infrastructure changes for a quarterly upgrade. To move them into production safely and traceably, which ITIL processes work together, and in what relationship?","options":["Configuration authorizes; availability packages; continuity deploys","Incident authorizes; problem packages; capacity deploys","Change authorizes; release plans/packages; deployment moves it into the live environment","Service level authorizes; security packages; incident deploys"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Change authorizes; release plans/packages; deployment moves it into the live environment</strong> — change management authorizes, release management plans and packages the set, and deployment management executes the move to production, a standard ITIL chain.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Incident authorizes; problem packages; capacity deploys</b>: these are restoration, root-cause, and resourcing processes, not release delivery.</span><span class='qd'><b>Configuration authorizes; availability packages; continuity deploys</b>: configuration records CIs and the others address uptime and disaster planning, not authorizing or packaging releases.</span><span class='qd'><b>Service level authorizes; security packages; incident deploys</b>: SLM manages agreements and incident restores service; neither packages nor deploys releases.</span>"},{"id":"D5-048","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"hard","q":"A cloud SOC must monitor a serverless, highly ephemeral environment where compute exists only for seconds. Which logging strategy is most essential for retaining investigative capability?","options":["Relying on host-based agents installed on long-lived servers","Storing logs solely on the ephemeral functions themselves","Capturing logs only after an incident is declared","Centralizing platform and application logs off the ephemeral compute in near real time"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Centralizing platform and application logs off the ephemeral compute in near real time</strong> — because serverless instances vanish quickly, logs must be shipped continuously to durable central storage to preserve investigative evidence.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Relying on host-based agents installed on long-lived servers</b>: there are no long-lived hosts to instrument in a serverless model.</span><span class='qd'><b>Capturing logs only after an incident is declared</b>: the ephemeral compute is already gone, so no evidence remains to capture.</span><span class='qd'><b>Storing logs solely on the ephemeral functions themselves</b>: those logs disappear when the function terminates.</span>"},{"id":"D5-049","domain":5,"obj":"5.1","diff":"hard","q":"A CCSP is choosing between a Type 1 and Type 2 hypervisor for a new production multi-tenant cloud platform. Which reasoning correctly drives selecting Type 1?","options":["Type 1 runs directly on hardware, reducing the trusted computing base and attack surface for multi-tenant isolation","Type 2 has a smaller trusted computing base because it lacks a host OS","Type 2 provides stronger tenant isolation because it runs inside a desktop OS","Type 1 requires a full host OS underneath, increasing patch burden"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Type 1 runs directly on hardware, reducing the trusted computing base and attack surface for multi-tenant isolation</strong> — a bare-metal hypervisor eliminates the underlying host OS, shrinking the TCB and strengthening tenant isolation for production.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Type 2 has a smaller trusted computing base because it lacks a host OS</b>: reversed; Type 2 requires a host OS and therefore has a larger TCB.</span><span class='qd'><b>Type 2 provides stronger tenant isolation because it runs inside a desktop OS</b>: running atop a general OS weakens, not strengthens, isolation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Type 1 requires a full host OS underneath, increasing patch burden</b>: false; Type 1 is bare-metal with no host OS beneath it.</span>"},{"id":"D5-050","domain":5,"obj":"5.3","diff":"hard","q":"After a major cloud outage, leadership wants assurance that the same class of failure will be systematically prevented, that services can survive a future disaster, and that lessons feed ongoing improvement. Which combination of ITIL processes addresses these three aims respectively?","options":["Incident, change, and capacity management","Problem management, service continuity management, and continual service improvement","Configuration, deployment, and release management","Availability, capacity, and service level management"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Problem management, service continuity management, and continual service improvement</strong> — problem management removes the root cause, service continuity management ensures survival of future disasters, and CSI feeds lessons into ongoing improvement, matching the three aims.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Incident, change, and capacity management</b>: restoration, controlled changes, and resourcing do not cover root-cause elimination plus disaster survival plus improvement together.</span><span class='qd'><b>Configuration, deployment, and release management</b>: these track CIs and deliver releases, not root cause, continuity, and improvement.</span><span class='qd'><b>Availability, capacity, and service level management</b>: these address uptime, resources, and agreements, not the specific trio requested.</span>"},{"id":"D5-051","domain":5,"obj":"5.4","diff":"easy","q":"An investigator is about to collect digital evidence from a suspect cloud workload. Which principle most directly governs the sequence in which evidence should be gathered?","options":["Collect the largest data stores first to maximize coverage","Collect only data that has already been backed up to durable storage","Collect the most volatile data first, then progressively less volatile data","Collect encrypted data last because it is hardest to read"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Collect the most volatile data first, then progressively less volatile data</strong> — the order-of-volatility principle preserves ephemeral artifacts (memory, running processes, network state) before they disappear.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Collect the largest data stores first</b>: size is irrelevant to evidentiary priority; prioritizing volume risks losing volatile data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Collect only data already backed up</b>: this ignores live volatile evidence that never reaches backups.</span><span class='qd'><b>Collect encrypted data last because it is hardest to read</b>: readability does not determine collection order; volatility does.</span>"},{"id":"D5-052","domain":5,"obj":"5.4","diff":"medium","q":"A forensic analyst must acquire a disk image from a virtual machine in an IaaS environment. Which approach best preserves evidentiary integrity while leveraging the cloud platform?","options":["Log into the guest OS and copy files with the native file manager","Reboot the VM into single-user mode and archive the running processes","Ask the tenant to email the relevant application logs","Take a provider snapshot of the volume and hash the exported image before and after transfer"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Take a provider snapshot of the volume and hash the exported image before and after transfer</strong> — snapshots capture a point-in-time copy without altering the source, and hashing proves the image was not modified in transit.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Copy files with the native file manager</b>: this alters timestamps and metadata and misses unallocated/slack space.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reboot into single-user mode</b>: rebooting destroys volatile memory and changes disk state, breaking integrity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ask the tenant to email logs</b>: this yields a curated subset with no chain of custody and no full image.</span>"},{"id":"D5-053","domain":5,"obj":"5.4","diff":"medium","q":"During a cloud incident, the forensics team needs to prove that evidence was handled without tampering from acquisition through court presentation. Which documentation practice most directly supports this?","options":["A maintained chain-of-custody record for each evidence item","A signed non-disclosure agreement with the cloud provider","A copy of the provider's SOC 2 Type II report","An asset inventory of all tenant virtual machines"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A maintained chain-of-custody record for each evidence item</strong> — it documents who handled each item, when, and why, establishing an unbroken, defensible trail.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Non-disclosure agreement</b>: confidentiality contracts do not track evidence handling.</span><span class='qd'><b>SOC 2 Type II report</b>: it attests to control operation, not to the handling of a specific piece of evidence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Asset inventory</b>: knowing which VMs exist does not prove evidence was untampered.</span>"},{"id":"D5-054","domain":5,"obj":"5.4","diff":"hard","q":"A multinational company must perform forensic acquisition of data stored in a cloud region located in another country. Which consideration should most shape the collection methodology?","options":["The provider's marketing claims about data residency","Jurisdictional and legal constraints on cross-border evidence collection","The number of availability zones in the target region","The tenant's preferred backup schedule"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Jurisdictional and legal constraints on cross-border evidence collection</strong> — data location determines which laws govern lawful access, admissibility, and privacy, and can bar or delay acquisition.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Provider marketing claims</b>: marketing is not a legal authority for lawful collection across borders.</span><span class='qd'><b>Number of availability zones</b>: zone count is an availability concern, not a legal one.</span><span class='qd'><b>Tenant's backup schedule</b>: backup timing is operational and does not resolve jurisdictional authority.</span>"},{"id":"D5-055","domain":5,"obj":"5.4","diff":"medium","q":"A cloud provider receives a request to preserve a customer's data for a pending investigation. Multi-tenancy complicates the response. What is the provider's primary forensic challenge here?","options":["Deciding which encryption algorithm to apply to the archive","Selecting a cheaper storage tier for the preserved data","Isolating and preserving only the target tenant's data without exposing other tenants","Reformatting the shared storage array to a forensic file system"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Isolating and preserving only the target tenant's data without exposing other tenants</strong> — commingled storage means the provider must scope collection to the subject tenant while protecting the confidentiality of unrelated tenants.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Choosing an encryption algorithm</b>: encryption of the archive is secondary to correctly scoping and isolating the data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Selecting a cheaper storage tier</b>: cost tiering is irrelevant to forensic isolation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reformatting shared storage</b>: reformatting would destroy other tenants' data and the evidence itself.</span>"},{"id":"D5-056","domain":5,"obj":"5.4","diff":"easy","q":"Which technique lets a forensic examiner verify that a collected evidence file has not changed since acquisition?","options":["Confirming the file opens without errors","Checking that the file size is a round number","Verifying the file has a recognizable extension","Comparing cryptographic hash values of the file"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Comparing cryptographic hash values of the file</strong> — a matching hash before and after proves bit-for-bit integrity of the evidence.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Confirming the file opens</b>: a file can open while its contents have been altered.</span><span class='qd'><b>Checking for a round file size</b>: file size is not a reliable integrity indicator.</span><span class='qd'><b>Verifying the extension</b>: extensions are trivially changed and prove nothing about content.</span>"},{"id":"D5-057","domain":5,"obj":"5.4","diff":"hard","q":"An enterprise wants contractual assurance that its cloud provider will cooperate with lawful forensic evidence collection. Where should this be established?","options":["In the service contract and SLA before an incident occurs","In the incident's after-action report","In a change ticket filed during the investigation","In the SIEM's alert configuration"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>In the service contract and SLA before an incident occurs</strong> — cooperation, access, timelines, and preservation duties must be negotiated up front because the customer rarely controls provider infrastructure.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>After-action report</b>: it is written after the fact and cannot compel prior cooperation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Change ticket during the investigation</b>: a ticket cannot create contractual obligations that were never agreed.</span><span class='qd'><b>SIEM alert configuration</b>: alerting is a detection setting, not a legal commitment.</span>"},{"id":"D5-058","domain":5,"obj":"5.4","diff":"medium","q":"A forensic team must capture the contents of a running container's memory before the orchestration platform reschedules the pod. Which characteristic makes this urgent?","options":["Container memory is written to durable object storage automatically","Ephemeral compute can be destroyed and recreated at any moment","Containers cannot be imaged under any circumstances","Memory contents are always encrypted at rest by default"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Ephemeral compute can be destroyed and recreated at any moment</strong> — orchestrators kill and reschedule pods dynamically, so volatile memory must be captured before the instance vanishes.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Memory written to object storage automatically</b>: RAM is not persisted to durable storage by default.</span><span class='qd'><b>Containers cannot be imaged</b>: memory and filesystem artifacts can be captured with the right tooling.</span><span class='qd'><b>Memory always encrypted at rest</b>: memory is volatile, not at-rest storage, so this is a category error.</span>"},{"id":"D5-059","domain":5,"obj":"5.4","diff":"easy","q":"What is the primary purpose of evidence management in a digital forensic process?","options":["To reduce cloud storage costs during an investigation","To accelerate the patching of the exploited vulnerability","To ensure evidence remains authentic, complete, and admissible","To notify all customers of the breach immediately"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>To ensure evidence remains authentic, complete, and admissible</strong> — evidence management preserves integrity and provenance so findings hold up under legal scrutiny.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Reduce storage costs</b>: cost control is unrelated to evidentiary value.</span><span class='qd'><b>Accelerate patching</b>: remediation is a separate incident-response activity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Notify customers immediately</b>: breach notification is a communication/legal task, not evidence management.</span>"},{"id":"D5-060","domain":5,"obj":"5.4","diff":"hard","q":"A cloud tenant lacks physical access to the hardware underlying its workloads. What does this most fundamentally change about traditional forensic acquisition?","options":["The tenant can seize the physical drives directly","Forensics becomes impossible in any cloud model","Only the regulator can acquire any evidence","The tenant must rely on provider-supplied APIs, snapshots, and logs to acquire evidence"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The tenant must rely on provider-supplied APIs, snapshots, and logs to acquire evidence</strong> — without hardware access, logical acquisition through the management plane replaces physical drive imaging.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Seize physical drives directly</b>: the tenant does not own or control the hardware.</span><span class='qd'><b>Forensics becomes impossible</b>: logical/cloud-native forensics remains fully possible.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only the regulator can acquire evidence</b>: tenants and providers routinely acquire evidence within contractual and legal bounds.</span>"},{"id":"D5-061","domain":5,"obj":"5.4","diff":"medium","q":"Which combination best preserves the admissibility of cloud audit logs collected as evidence?","options":["Write-once storage with timestamps, hashing, and documented custody","Storing logs in a mutable spreadsheet edited by analysts","A screenshot of the log console pasted into a report","Logs summarized verbally in a status meeting"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Write-once storage with timestamps, hashing, and documented custody</strong> — immutability plus integrity proofs and a custody trail make logs defensible in legal proceedings.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Mutable spreadsheet edited by analysts</b>: editable storage destroys the presumption of integrity.</span><span class='qd'><b>A screenshot pasted into a report</b>: a screenshot is easily manipulated and lacks completeness and custody.</span><span class='qd'><b>Verbal summary in a meeting</b>: verbal recollection is neither complete nor verifiable.</span>"},{"id":"D5-062","domain":5,"obj":"5.4","diff":"medium","q":"A forensic acquisition plan references ISO/IEC 27037. What does this standard primarily guide?","options":["Pricing models for cloud storage tiers","Identification, collection, acquisition, and preservation of digital evidence","The design of hypervisor scheduling algorithms","Employee onboarding and awareness training"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Identification, collection, acquisition, and preservation of digital evidence</strong> — ISO/IEC 27037 provides internationally recognized guidance for handling potential digital evidence.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Pricing models for storage tiers</b>: pricing is a commercial concern, not a forensic standard.</span><span class='qd'><b>Hypervisor scheduling algorithms</b>: this is a virtualization design topic, unrelated to evidence handling.</span><span class='qd'><b>Onboarding and awareness training</b>: security awareness is covered by other standards, not 27037.</span>"},{"id":"D5-063","domain":5,"obj":"5.4","diff":"easy","q":"When acquiring evidence, why should investigators work from a forensic copy rather than the original data whenever possible?","options":["Copies are always smaller and faster to search","Copies automatically redact sensitive information","Working on a copy preserves the original in an unaltered state","Originals cannot be hashed"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Working on a copy preserves the original in an unaltered state</strong> — analyzing a verified duplicate keeps the source pristine for validation and court.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Copies are always smaller/faster</b>: a forensic image is the same size as the source, not smaller.</span><span class='qd'><b>Copies automatically redact data</b>: forensic copies are bit-for-bit duplicates, not redacted.</span><span class='qd'><b>Originals cannot be hashed</b>: originals are routinely hashed to verify the copy.</span>"},{"id":"D5-064","domain":5,"obj":"5.4","diff":"hard","q":"A legal hold is issued during a cloud investigation, but the tenant's lifecycle policy is set to auto-delete objects after 30 days. What must the security operations team do?","options":["Let the lifecycle policy run to save storage costs","Immediately export everything to a personal device","Rotate the encryption keys to lock the data","Suspend the deletion mechanism to preserve potentially relevant data"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Suspend the deletion mechanism to preserve potentially relevant data</strong> — a legal hold overrides routine retention and requires stopping automated deletion to avoid spoliation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Let the lifecycle policy run</b>: allowing deletion under a hold is spoliation and can carry sanctions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Export to a personal device</b>: uncontrolled export breaks chain of custody and confidentiality.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rotate encryption keys</b>: rotating keys risks rendering data unrecoverable and does not satisfy a hold.</span>"},{"id":"D5-065","domain":5,"obj":"5.4","diff":"medium","q":"An examiner needs to demonstrate non-repudiation for evidence handed off between three analysts. Which control best supports this?","options":["Digitally signed transfer records at each handoff","A shared password known to all three analysts","Deleting the evidence after each analysis","Storing the evidence on a public web server"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Digitally signed transfer records at each handoff</strong> — signatures bind each analyst to their custody, preventing later denial of handling.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Shared password</b>: a shared secret makes actions indistinguishable and defeats accountability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Deleting evidence after analysis</b>: destroying evidence undermines the entire case.</span><span class='qd'><b>Public web server</b>: exposing evidence violates confidentiality and integrity.</span>"},{"id":"D5-066","domain":5,"obj":"5.5","diff":"easy","q":"Which stakeholder must a cloud security operations team typically notify when a breach triggers a statutory reporting obligation?","options":["The nearest hardware vendor","The relevant regulator or supervisory authority","The building facilities manager","A competitor in the same market"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The relevant regulator or supervisory authority</strong> — breach-notification laws obligate reporting to the designated regulator within defined timeframes.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Nearest hardware vendor</b>: a hardware vendor has no statutory right to breach notice.</span><span class='qd'><b>Facilities manager</b>: physical facilities staff are not a data-protection reporting party.</span><span class='qd'><b>A competitor</b>: disclosing to a competitor serves no obligation and harms the organization.</span>"},{"id":"D5-067","domain":5,"obj":"5.5","diff":"medium","q":"During a major cloud outage, the operations team must coordinate messaging across customers, the provider, and regulators. What is the most important reason to designate a single communication owner?","options":["To reduce the number of people who must be paid overtime","To keep the provider from learning about the outage","To ensure consistent, accurate, and timely messaging to all parties","To avoid documenting the incident"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>To ensure consistent, accurate, and timely messaging to all parties</strong> — a single owner prevents conflicting statements and controls disclosure timing across stakeholders.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Reduce overtime pay</b>: cost is not the driver for communication ownership.</span><span class='qd'><b>Keep the provider uninformed</b>: the provider is a key party who must be engaged, not excluded.</span><span class='qd'><b>Avoid documenting the incident</b>: documentation is required, not something to avoid.</span>"},{"id":"D5-068","domain":5,"obj":"5.5","diff":"medium","q":"A SaaS customer wants to know, in advance, exactly how the provider will communicate during a security incident. Where is this expectation best captured?","options":["In the provider's internal chat channel","In a one-off email after the first incident","In the marketing brochure","In an incident communication plan and the contract/SLA"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>In an incident communication plan and the contract/SLA</strong> — pre-agreed communication commitments define channels, timelines, and roles before an incident occurs.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Provider's internal chat</b>: internal channels are not visible or binding to the customer.</span><span class='qd'><b>One-off email after the first incident</b>: reacting after the fact provides no prior assurance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Marketing brochure</b>: marketing is not a contractual commitment.</span>"},{"id":"D5-069","domain":5,"obj":"5.5","diff":"hard","q":"A cloud provider discovers a vulnerability that affects many tenants but has not yet been exploited. What is the most defensible communication approach?","options":["Notify affected customers with coordinated, actionable guidance while limiting exploitable detail","Publicly disclose full exploit details immediately to force patching","Say nothing until a tenant is breached","Notify only the largest revenue customers"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Notify affected customers with coordinated, actionable guidance while limiting exploitable detail</strong> — responsible, coordinated disclosure informs those at risk without handing attackers a blueprint.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Publicly disclose full exploit details immediately</b>: full detail before mitigation arms attackers.</span><span class='qd'><b>Say nothing until a breach</b>: silence leaves customers unable to protect themselves.</span><span class='qd'><b>Notify only the largest customers</b>: selective notice leaves other affected tenants exposed and is inequitable.</span>"},{"id":"D5-070","domain":5,"obj":"5.5","diff":"easy","q":"Which document typically defines the agreed response and communication timeframes between a cloud provider and its customer?","options":["The provider's org chart","The service level agreement (SLA)","The data center floor plan","The employee handbook"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The service level agreement (SLA)</strong> — the SLA specifies measurable commitments including response and notification timeframes.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Org chart</b>: it shows reporting lines, not service commitments.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data center floor plan</b>: a physical layout has no bearing on communication timeframes.</span><span class='qd'><b>Employee handbook</b>: internal HR policy does not bind the customer relationship.</span>"},{"id":"D5-071","domain":5,"obj":"5.5","diff":"medium","q":"A partner integrates with your cloud service via API. During an incident affecting shared data flows, which principle should guide what you share with them?","options":["Share everything, including other customers' data, for transparency","Share nothing, since partners are external","Share information relevant to their exposure on a need-to-know basis","Share only after the incident is fully closed"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Share information relevant to their exposure on a need-to-know basis</strong> — partners must receive enough to protect shared data flows without over-disclosing unrelated or third-party information.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Share everything including other customers' data</b>: exposing others' data violates confidentiality obligations.</span><span class='qd'><b>Share nothing</b>: withholding relevant risk information can worsen the incident for both parties.</span><span class='qd'><b>Share only after closure</b>: partners need timely notice to act, not a post-mortem.</span>"},{"id":"D5-072","domain":5,"obj":"5.5","diff":"hard","q":"An organization operates in multiple countries with differing breach-notification laws. What is the safest communication strategy when a single incident spans several jurisdictions?","options":["Apply only the least strict jurisdiction's requirements","Delay all notifications until every law is fully researched","Notify only the headquarters country's regulator","Map each affected jurisdiction's obligations and satisfy the strictest applicable timelines and content"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Map each affected jurisdiction's obligations and satisfy the strictest applicable timelines and content</strong> — meeting the most stringent applicable requirement per jurisdiction keeps the organization compliant everywhere it operates.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Apply the least strict jurisdiction</b>: this violates stricter laws that also apply.</span><span class='qd'><b>Delay all notifications until fully researched</b>: statutory clocks run regardless, so delay causes noncompliance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Notify only headquarters' regulator</b>: obligations attach where data subjects and operations are, not just the HQ.</span>"},{"id":"D5-073","domain":5,"obj":"5.5","diff":"medium","q":"A regulator requests evidence of how a cloud incident was handled. What should the operations team prioritize when responding?","options":["Accurate, complete, and timely information consistent with legal counsel","An informal phone call with no records","Only favorable details that minimize the incident","A request to extend the deadline indefinitely"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Accurate, complete, and timely information consistent with legal counsel</strong> — regulators require truthful, complete responses, coordinated with counsel to protect the organization's legal position.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Informal call with no records</b>: undocumented responses fail regulatory expectations and create disputes.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only favorable details</b>: selective disclosure to a regulator can constitute misrepresentation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Indefinite extension request</b>: statutory deadlines cannot be waived at will and stalling harms credibility.</span>"},{"id":"D5-074","domain":5,"obj":"5.5","diff":"easy","q":"Why should a cloud customer maintain up-to-date contact information for its provider's security and support teams?","options":["To increase the provider's marketing outreach","To enable rapid escalation and coordination during an incident","To reduce the customer's monthly invoice","To satisfy the provider's hardware refresh cycle"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>To enable rapid escalation and coordination during an incident</strong> — current contacts prevent delays when time-sensitive escalation is needed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Increase marketing outreach</b>: contact upkeep is for operations, not marketing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reduce the invoice</b>: contact records have no billing effect.</span><span class='qd'><b>Hardware refresh cycle</b>: provider hardware cycles are unrelated to customer contact lists.</span>"},{"id":"D5-075","domain":5,"obj":"5.5","diff":"hard","q":"After containing a breach, executives want to notify the media before affected customers are informed. From a CCSP judgment standpoint, what is the primary concern?","options":["Media coverage will improve the stock price","Customers do not need to be told at all","Affected parties should be informed appropriately before broad public disclosure to meet obligations and trust","Media notification satisfies all regulatory duties"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Affected parties should be informed appropriately before broad public disclosure to meet obligations and trust</strong> — notifying the affected and regulators in the proper sequence upholds legal duties and stakeholder trust.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Media coverage improves stock price</b>: financial optics do not override notification obligations.</span><span class='qd'><b>Media notification satisfies regulatory duties</b>: a press release does not fulfill formal regulatory or affected-party notice.</span><span class='qd'><b>Customers do not need to be told</b>: affected customers generally must be notified under law and contract.</span>"},{"id":"D5-076","domain":5,"obj":"5.5","diff":"medium","q":"A cloud vendor's subprocessor suffers an incident affecting your data. Who is generally responsible for communicating with your organization about it?","options":["The subprocessor's marketing department","Your own board of directors alone","No one, because subprocessors are invisible","Your direct vendor, per the contractual chain"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Your direct vendor, per the contractual chain</strong> — the vendor you contracted with is accountable for its subprocessors and must relay incident information to you.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Subprocessor's marketing</b>: you have no direct contract or channel with the subprocessor.</span><span class='qd'><b>Your board alone</b>: the board is an internal audience, not the source of vendor notice.</span><span class='qd'><b>No one</b>: subprocessor obligations flow through the vendor contract, so notice is required.</span>"},{"id":"D5-077","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"easy","q":"What is the primary function of a Security Operations Center (SOC) in a cloud environment?","options":["Continuous monitoring, detection, and response to security events","Designing the corporate website","Negotiating discounts on cloud compute","Approving employee expense reports"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Continuous monitoring, detection, and response to security events</strong> — a SOC provides ongoing visibility and coordinated response across the environment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Negotiating compute discounts</b>: procurement is not a SOC function.</span><span class='qd'><b>Designing the website</b>: web design is unrelated to security monitoring.</span><span class='qd'><b>Approving expense reports</b>: finance approvals are outside SOC scope.</span>"},{"id":"D5-078","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"easy","q":"Which technology aggregates and correlates log data from many cloud sources to support detection and analysis?","options":["A DNS resolver","A SIEM platform","A load balancer","A container registry"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A SIEM platform</strong> — Security Information and Event Management systems centralize, correlate, and analyze logs to surface security events.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Load balancer</b>: it distributes traffic, it does not correlate security logs.</span><span class='qd'><b>DNS resolver</b>: it translates names to addresses, not a log-analysis tool.</span><span class='qd'><b>Container registry</b>: it stores images, not security events.</span>"},{"id":"D5-079","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"medium","q":"A SOC is overwhelmed by low-value alerts and misses real threats. Which improvement most directly addresses alert fatigue?","options":["Disabling all logging to reduce noise","Forwarding every raw log to every analyst's inbox","Tuning correlation rules and enriching alerts to prioritize high-fidelity signals","Hiring more analysts without changing tooling"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Tuning correlation rules and enriching alerts to prioritize high-fidelity signals</strong> — refining rules and adding context reduces false positives so analysts focus on meaningful events.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling all logging</b>: removing telemetry blinds the SOC and destroys detection.</span><span class='qd'><b>Hiring more analysts without tooling changes</b>: more staff on the same noise still drowns in false positives.</span><span class='qd'><b>Forwarding raw logs to inboxes</b>: dumping raw data increases noise rather than prioritizing it.</span>"},{"id":"D5-080","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"medium","q":"During incident management, which phase focuses on limiting the scope and impact of an active security event?","options":["Preparation","Lessons learned","Recovery","Containment"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Containment</strong> — containment stops the spread and limits damage while the team works toward eradication and recovery.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Lessons learned</b>: this occurs after the incident to improve future response.</span><span class='qd'><b>Preparation</b>: preparation happens before an incident, building readiness.</span><span class='qd'><b>Recovery</b>: recovery restores systems after the threat is removed, not while limiting active spread.</span>"},{"id":"D5-081","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"hard","q":"A cloud SOC wants to detect novel attacks that signature-based tools miss. Which capability is most appropriate to add?","options":["Behavioral analytics and anomaly detection, including AI/ML-assisted monitoring","A larger fixed signature database only","More static allow/deny firewall rules","Longer password expiration intervals"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Behavioral analytics and anomaly detection, including AI/ML-assisted monitoring</strong> — modeling normal behavior surfaces deviations that signatures cannot anticipate.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>More static firewall rules</b>: static rules cannot recognize previously unseen behavior.</span><span class='qd'><b>Larger signature database only</b>: signatures still only match known patterns, missing novel attacks.</span><span class='qd'><b>Longer password expiration</b>: password policy does not detect attacks.</span>"},{"id":"D5-082","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"medium","q":"A vulnerability assessment of a cloud environment returns hundreds of findings. What should most influence the order in which they are remediated?","options":["Alphabetical order of the affected hostnames","Risk-based prioritization considering exploitability, exposure, and business impact","The oldest ticket number first","The color of the severity label only"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Risk-based prioritization considering exploitability, exposure, and business impact</strong> — remediation should target the findings posing the greatest real-world risk first.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Alphabetical order</b>: naming has no relationship to risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Color of the label only</b>: a label without context can misrank actual exposure and impact.</span><span class='qd'><b>Oldest ticket first</b>: age alone ignores current exploitability and impact.</span>"},{"id":"D5-083","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"easy","q":"What distinguishes a honeypot from other network security controls in a SOC's toolkit?","options":["It load-balances requests across servers","It encrypts all traffic between clients and servers","It is a decoy resource designed to attract and study attackers","It stores production customer records"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>It is a decoy resource designed to attract and study attackers</strong> — honeypots lure adversaries away from real assets and reveal their techniques.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypts all traffic</b>: encryption is the role of TLS/VPN, not a honeypot.</span><span class='qd'><b>Load-balances requests</b>: that is a load balancer's job.</span><span class='qd'><b>Stores production records</b>: a honeypot intentionally holds no real data of value.</span>"},{"id":"D5-084","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"hard","q":"A SOC ingests logs from IaaS, PaaS, and SaaS services with different formats and time zones. What is the most important preprocessing step for reliable correlation?","options":["Discarding logs that are not in one preferred format","Compressing logs to save storage before analysis","Renaming the log files to match the SIEM vendor","Normalizing formats and synchronizing timestamps to a common time reference"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Normalizing formats and synchronizing timestamps to a common time reference</strong> — consistent fields and a shared clock let the SIEM correlate events across heterogeneous sources accurately.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Discarding non-preferred formats</b>: dropping sources creates blind spots.</span><span class='qd'><b>Renaming log files</b>: file names do not affect event correlation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Compressing to save storage</b>: compression is a storage optimization, not a correlation enabler.</span>"},{"id":"D5-085","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"medium","q":"An organization wants to reduce the time between detection and response in its cloud SOC. Which capability most directly achieves this?","options":["Automated playbooks and orchestration (SOAR) for routine response actions","A larger monthly report to executives","A quarterly manual review of all alerts","A longer log retention period"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Automated playbooks and orchestration (SOAR) for routine response actions</strong> — orchestration executes predefined responses instantly, shrinking mean time to respond.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Quarterly manual review</b>: infrequent manual work lengthens, not shortens, response time.</span><span class='qd'><b>Larger executive report</b>: reporting does not accelerate response.</span><span class='qd'><b>Longer retention</b>: keeping logs longer aids investigation but not response speed.</span>"},{"id":"D5-086","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"easy","q":"Which control actively blocks detected malicious traffic rather than only alerting on it?","options":["A syslog collector","An intrusion prevention system (IPS)","An intrusion detection system (IDS)","A read-only dashboard"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>An intrusion prevention system (IPS)</strong> — an IPS sits inline and can drop or block malicious traffic in real time.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Intrusion detection system</b>: an IDS alerts on threats but does not block them.</span><span class='qd'><b>Syslog collector</b>: it gathers logs, it does not act on traffic.</span><span class='qd'><b>Read-only dashboard</b>: a dashboard displays data and takes no action.</span>"},{"id":"D5-087","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"medium","q":"A SOC analyst must decide whether an event is a security incident or a routine anomaly. Which practice best supports consistent decisions?","options":["Escalating every event as critical","Relying on each analyst's personal judgment with no guidance","Documented incident classification criteria and severity thresholds","Waiting until end of shift to review events"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Documented incident classification criteria and severity thresholds</strong> — defined criteria produce consistent, repeatable triage across analysts and shifts.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Personal judgment with no guidance</b>: unguided judgment yields inconsistent, non-defensible decisions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Escalating every event as critical</b>: over-escalation causes fatigue and hides true criticals.</span><span class='qd'><b>Waiting until end of shift</b>: delayed triage lets active incidents worsen.</span>"},{"id":"D5-088","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"hard","q":"A cloud provider offers a shared, managed SOC, but a regulated tenant needs assurance that its data is monitored to its own standard. What should the tenant do?","options":["Assume the provider's SOC covers all tenant-specific obligations","Disable its own logging to avoid duplication","Rely solely on the provider's SOC 3 report","Define monitoring requirements contractually and validate coverage of its shared-responsibility portion"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Define monitoring requirements contractually and validate coverage of its shared-responsibility portion</strong> — the tenant remains accountable for its side of the responsibility split and must confirm the SOC meets its specific needs.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Assume the SOC covers everything</b>: shared responsibility means the tenant retains obligations the provider does not.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rely solely on a SOC 3 report</b>: a general-use SOC 3 lacks the detail to validate tenant-specific coverage.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disable own logging</b>: removing tenant-side telemetry creates gaps the provider cannot see.</span>"},{"id":"D5-089","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"medium","q":"Which metric best reflects how quickly a SOC identifies that an incident has occurred?","options":["Mean time to detect (MTTD)","Monthly cloud spend","Total number of firewall rules","Number of dashboards deployed"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Mean time to detect (MTTD)</strong> — MTTD measures the average interval from event occurrence to detection, a core SOC performance indicator.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Number of firewall rules</b>: rule count says nothing about detection speed.</span><span class='qd'><b>Monthly cloud spend</b>: cost is a financial metric, not a detection metric.</span><span class='qd'><b>Number of dashboards</b>: having dashboards does not measure how fast detection happens.</span>"},{"id":"D5-090","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"easy","q":"What is the main purpose of threat intelligence feeds in a cloud SOC?","options":["To provision new virtual machines automatically","To provide context on known indicators and adversary activity for better detection","To bill customers for network usage","To replace the need for any logging"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>To provide context on known indicators and adversary activity for better detection</strong> — intelligence feeds enrich monitoring with current indicators of compromise and threat context.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Bill customers for usage</b>: billing is a metering function, unrelated to intelligence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Provision VMs automatically</b>: provisioning is an orchestration task.</span><span class='qd'><b>Replace logging</b>: intelligence complements logs, it does not replace them.</span>"},{"id":"D5-091","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"medium","q":"A SOC detects lateral movement inside a cloud tenancy. Which immediate action best limits the attacker while preserving forensic value?","options":["Power off every workload without recording state","Ignore it until the next scheduled scan","Isolate affected resources via network segmentation while capturing volatile data","Immediately delete the compromised instances"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Isolate affected resources via network segmentation while capturing volatile data</strong> — isolation halts spread, and capturing volatile data first preserves evidence for investigation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Power off everything without recording state</b>: powering off destroys volatile evidence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Delete compromised instances</b>: deletion eradicates evidence and disrupts root-cause analysis.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore until next scan</b>: inaction lets the attacker expand access.</span>"},{"id":"D5-092","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"hard","q":"An organization runs both agent-based and agentless monitoring across cloud workloads. What is the strongest reason to combine the two?","options":["Agents alone are always cheaper, so combining wastes money","Combining them removes the need for a SIEM","Agentless monitoring can fully replace all agents in every case","Together they close visibility gaps: agents give deep host telemetry, agentless gives broad coverage of ephemeral and unmanaged resources"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Together they close visibility gaps: agents give deep host telemetry, agentless gives broad coverage of ephemeral and unmanaged resources</strong> — the two approaches complement each other for comprehensive cloud visibility.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Agents always cheaper so combining wastes money</b>: cost is not the point; coverage is, and agents miss ephemeral assets.</span><span class='qd'><b>Agentless fully replaces agents</b>: agentless typically lacks deep in-host runtime detail.</span><span class='qd'><b>Combining removes the need for a SIEM</b>: telemetry still needs a SIEM to correlate and analyze.</span>"},{"id":"D5-093","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"medium","q":"A SOC wants to verify its detection capabilities against realistic attacker techniques before a real incident. Which activity is most appropriate?","options":["Purple-team exercises that test and tune detection collaboratively","Waiting for an actual breach to test readiness","Turning off alerting to reduce load","Deleting historical logs to start fresh"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Purple-team exercises that test and tune detection collaboratively</strong> — offensive and defensive teams working together validate and improve detections proactively.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Turning off alerting</b>: disabling alerts removes detection, the opposite of testing it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Waiting for an actual breach</b>: real incidents are a costly, unacceptable way to test readiness.</span><span class='qd'><b>Deleting historical logs</b>: destroying history removes baselines needed for detection tuning.</span>"},{"id":"D5-094","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"easy","q":"Which practice ensures that SOC monitoring keeps pace with newly deployed cloud resources?","options":["Monitoring only the resources deployed on day one","Automatically onboarding new resources into logging and monitoring pipelines","Manually adding each resource months after deployment","Excluding auto-scaled instances from monitoring"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Automatically onboarding new resources into logging and monitoring pipelines</strong> — automation keeps coverage current in dynamic, elastic cloud environments.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Manually adding months later</b>: delays leave new assets unmonitored and exposed.</span><span class='qd'><b>Monitoring only day-one resources</b>: this ignores everything provisioned afterward.</span><span class='qd'><b>Excluding auto-scaled instances</b>: elastic instances are frequent attack targets and must be monitored.</span>"},{"id":"D5-095","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"medium","q":"After an incident is resolved, the SOC conducts a review to prevent recurrence. What is the primary output of this phase?","options":["A press release only","A bill for the incident response time","Documented lessons learned and actionable improvements","A new marketing campaign"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Documented lessons learned and actionable improvements</strong> — the post-incident review captures what happened and drives concrete changes to prevent recurrence.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A bill for response time</b>: cost accounting is not the purpose of the review.</span><span class='qd'><b>A press release only</b>: external messaging is separate from internal improvement.</span><span class='qd'><b>A marketing campaign</b>: marketing is unrelated to incident learning.</span>"},{"id":"D5-096","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"hard","q":"A cloud SOC must monitor a serverless application where functions run for milliseconds. What monitoring adaptation is most necessary?","options":["Relying on periodic host antivirus scans","Scanning the underlying servers the tenant cannot access","Installing a traditional endpoint agent on each function","Capturing per-invocation logs and traces because there is no persistent host to inspect"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Capturing per-invocation logs and traces because there is no persistent host to inspect</strong> — serverless has no durable host, so visibility comes from function-level telemetry and tracing.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Periodic host antivirus scans</b>: there is no persistent host to scan on a schedule.</span><span class='qd'><b>Installing an endpoint agent per function</b>: functions are ephemeral and provider-managed; agents cannot be installed.</span><span class='qd'><b>Scanning underlying servers</b>: the tenant has no access to the provider's serverless infrastructure.</span>"},{"id":"D5-097","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"medium","q":"A SOC relies on a single cloud region's logging service that itself went down during an outage. Which design change best improves monitoring resilience?","options":["Forwarding logs to a separate, redundant location independent of the monitored environment","Storing logs only on the affected workloads","Encrypting logs with a key stored only on the failed system","Reducing how often logs are collected"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Forwarding logs to a separate, redundant location independent of the monitored environment</strong> — decoupling log storage from the monitored system ensures visibility survives an outage.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Storing logs on the workloads</b>: if the workload fails, its logs are lost too.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reducing collection frequency</b>: less frequent collection reduces visibility, not resilience.</span><span class='qd'><b>Key stored only on the failed system</b>: a lost system means lost key means unrecoverable logs.</span>"},{"id":"D5-098","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"easy","q":"What is the main goal of vulnerability assessments performed by a cloud security operations team?","options":["To increase the number of open ports","To identify and evaluate weaknesses so they can be prioritized and remediated","To generate revenue from the assessment reports","To replace the incident response plan"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>To identify and evaluate weaknesses so they can be prioritized and remediated</strong> — assessments surface exploitable weaknesses to drive risk-based remediation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Generate revenue from reports</b>: assessments are a security function, not a revenue source.</span><span class='qd'><b>Increase open ports</b>: the goal is to reduce exposure, not increase it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Replace the incident response plan</b>: assessment and IR are complementary, not substitutes.</span>"},{"id":"D5-099","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"hard","q":"A SOC finds that its cloud vulnerability scanner reports issues the provider is contractually responsible for patching. What is the most appropriate operational response?","options":["Attempt to patch the provider's underlying infrastructure directly","Publicly disclose the provider's infrastructure flaw","Track the finding, confirm it falls to the provider under shared responsibility, and coordinate remediation with them","Ignore the finding permanently"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Track the finding, confirm it falls to the provider under shared responsibility, and coordinate remediation with them</strong> — the tenant documents the issue and engages the accountable provider rather than acting outside its control boundary.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Patch provider infrastructure directly</b>: the tenant has no access or authority to patch provider layers.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore the finding permanently</b>: unmanaged risk persists and may still affect the tenant.</span><span class='qd'><b>Publicly disclose the flaw</b>: uncoordinated public disclosure breaches contract and endangers others.</span>"},{"id":"D5-100","domain":5,"obj":"5.6","diff":"medium","q":"An organization is deciding between running its own SOC and using a managed detection and response (MDR) service for its cloud estate. Which factor should weigh most heavily in a CCSP-aligned decision?","options":["Which option has the flashiest dashboard","The color scheme of the SOC software","Which vendor sponsors the most conferences","Whether the organization can staff and sustain 24/7 expertise and coverage in-house"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Whether the organization can staff and sustain 24/7 expertise and coverage in-house</strong> — the decision hinges on the ability to maintain continuous, skilled coverage, which drives the build-versus-buy choice.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Flashiest dashboard</b>: visual appeal does not determine detection effectiveness.</span><span class='qd'><b>Conference sponsorship</b>: marketing presence is irrelevant to operational capability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Color scheme</b>: cosmetics have no bearing on security outcomes.</span>"}]);
